3. Explain the internal working of a HashMap in Java 8. What happens during a hash collision?

Answer:
HashMap stores key-value pairs in an array of Node objects (buckets).

Internal Structure (Java 8+):

· Array of Node<K,V> called table (default capacity: 16)
· Each Node contains: hash, key, value, and next pointer
· Buckets transition from linked list to Red-Black Tree when threshold (8) is reached

Put Operation:

1. Calculate key's hash: hash = key.hashCode() ^ (key.hashCode() >>> 16)
2. Determine bucket index: index = (n - 1) & hash (n = table length)
3. If bucket is empty, create new Node and store
4. If collision occurs, check if key exists:
   · If key exists, replace value
   · If new key, append Node to existing chain/treap

Hash Collision Resolution:

```
Key1 -> Hash1 -> Index 5 (Node1)
Key2 -> Hash2 -> Index 5 (Node1 -> Node2)
Key3 -> Hash3 -> Index 5 (Node1 -> Node2 -> Node3)
```

Example:

```java
// HashMap with 2 keys having same hash
HashMap<String, String> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put("key1", "value1");
map.put("key2", "value2");
// Both keys are stored in same bucket as a linked list/Red-Black tree
```

4. When does a HashMap bucket transition from a Linked List to a Red-Black Tree? What is the threshold?

Answer:

· Threshold: When the number of elements in a bucket exceeds TREEIFY_THRESHOLD = 8
· Transition Triggers:
  · Same bucket has 9 or more elements
  · Table size >= MIN_TREEIFY_CAPACITY = 64
  · Both conditions must be met (if table size < 64, table resizing occurs instead)

Why Red-Black Tree?

· O(log n) search time vs O(n) for linked list
· More efficient for hash-intensive collisions
· Red-Black tree maintains balanced structure

Untreeify Threshold: When bucket size reduces to <= 6 (UNTREEIFY_THRESHOLD)

Example:

```java
// This can trigger treeification if all keys hash to same bucket
for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    map.put("key" + i, "value" + i); // All keys may end up in same bucket
}
```

5. What is the difference between fail-fast and fail-safe iterators? Give examples.

Answer:

Feature Fail-Fast Fail-Safe
Behavior Throws ConcurrentModificationException if collection modified during iteration Doesn't throw exception; works on copy of collection
Implementation Uses a modCount counter to detect changes Operates on a snapshot/clone
Memory Overhead Lower Higher (creates copy)
Examples ArrayList, HashMap, HashSet ConcurrentHashMap, CopyOnWriteArrayList

Example:

```java
// Fail-Fast (throws ConcurrentModificationException)
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("A", "B", "C"));
Iterator<String> iter = list.iterator();
while (iter.hasNext()) {
    String s = iter.next();
    list.remove(s); // Throws ConcurrentModificationException
}

// Fail-Safe (safe modification)
List<String> safeList = new CopyOnWriteArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("A", "B", "C"));
Iterator<String> safeIter = safeList.iterator();
while (safeIter.hasNext()) {
    String s = safeIter.next();
    safeList.remove(s); // Allowed, works on copy
}

// ConcurrentHashMap (fail-safe for multi-threaded)
ConcurrentHashMap<String, String> concurrentMap = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
concurrentMap.put("key1", "value1");
Iterator<Map.Entry<String, String>> entryIter = concurrentMap.entrySet().iterator();
while (entryIter.hasNext()) {
    Map.Entry<String, String> entry = entryIter.next();
    concurrentMap.remove("key1"); // Safe, no exception
}
```

6. How does ConcurrentHashMap achieve thread safety without locking the entire map?

Answer:
ConcurrentHashMap uses Segment-based locking (pre-Java 8) and Node-level locking (Java 8+).

Java 8 Implementation:

· Node-Level Locking: Only locks individual buckets (nodes) or subtrees
· CAS Operations: Uses Compare-And-Swap for non-blocking operations
· TreeBins: Uses a combination of CAS and synchronized for tree nodes
· size(): Not accurate in real-time but approximate (uses sumCount() method)

Key Optimizations:

1. put(): Only locks the specific bucket
   ```java
   // Simplified concept
   final V putVal(K key, V value, boolean onlyIfAbsent) {
       // ... CAS for null bucket
       synchronized (f) { // Lock only the bucket, not entire map
           // put logic
       }
   }
   ```
2. get(): Completely lock-free (uses volatile reads)
3. resize(): Lock-free while old segments remain accessible

Comparison:

· Hashtable: Synchronizes entire table (high contention)
· ConcurrentHashMap: Fine-grained locking (low contention)

7. Explain the Java Exception hierarchy. What is the difference between Checked and Unchecked exceptions?

Answer:

```
Throwable
├── Error (Unchecked) - System-level errors (OutOfMemoryError, StackOverflowError)
└── Exception
    ├── IOException, SQLException, InterruptedException (Checked exceptions)
    └── RuntimeException (Unchecked)
        ├── NullPointerException
        ├── IllegalArgumentException
        ├── ArithmeticException
        └── ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
```

Checked Exceptions:

· Must be handled at compile time using try-catch or throws
· Represent recoverable conditions
· Examples: IOException, SQLException, FileNotFoundException

Unchecked Exceptions (RuntimeException):

· Not checked at compile time
· Represent programming errors
· Examples: NullPointerException, ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException

Example:

```java
// Checked Exception - must handle
try {
    FileInputStream file = new FileInputStream("file.txt");
} catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
    // Must handle or declare throws
}

// Unchecked Exception - optional to handle
String str = null;
str.toString(); // NullPointerException - runtime error
```

8. What is the purpose of the hashCode() and equals() contract? What happens if you override one but not the other?

Answer:
The contract between hashCode() and equals() states:

1. If a.equals(b) is true, then a.hashCode() == b.hashCode() must also be true
2. If a.hashCode() == b.hashCode(), equals() may be true or false (not guaranteed)
3. Consistent results when called repeatedly on the same object

Consequences of Breaking Contract:

Override only equals() (not hashCode()):

· Objects that are logically equal may have different hash codes
· Violation when using HashSet, HashMap, or HashTable
· Objects may be stored in different buckets, breaking functionality

Override only hashCode() (not equals()):

· Two different objects could have same hash code
· Leads to incorrect contains() checks in collections
· May cause keys to be considered equal incorrectly

Example:

```java
class Employee {
    private String id;
    private String name;

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (this == o) return true;
        if (!(o instanceof Employee)) return false;
        Employee e = (Employee) o;
        return Objects.equals(id, e.id);
    }
    
    // If equals is overridden, must override hashCode
    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return Objects.hash(id);
    }
}
```

9. Explain the use of the volatile keyword in Java multi-threading.

Answer:
The volatile keyword ensures variable visibility across threads by:

1. Memory Visibility: Changes to volatile variables are immediately visible to all threads
2. Happens-Before Guarantee: Writes to volatile variables happen before subsequent reads
3. Cache Coherence: Prevents thread-local caching of the variable

Key Points:

· Only guarantees visibility, not atomicity
· Works as a lightweight synchronization alternative to synchronized
· Cannot be used with non-atomic operations (x++ is not atomic even with volatile)
· Often used for flags and state variables

Example:

```java
// Without volatile - may cause infinite loop
class SharedFlag {
    private boolean running = true; // Not volatile
    
    public void run() {
        while (running) { 
            // Thread may cache running = true forever
        }
    }
    public void stop() {
        running = false; // May not be visible to other threads
    }
}

// With volatile - guarantees visibility
class SharedFlag {
    private volatile boolean running = true;
    
    public void run() {
        while (running) { 
            // Always reads from main memory
        }
    }
    public void stop() {
        running = false; // Immediately visible to all threads
    }
}
```

10. What is the difference between ExecutorService.submit() and ExecutorService.execute()?

Answer:

Feature execute(Runnable command) submit(Callable<T> task)
Return Type void Future<T>
Result Access No result retrieval Can get result via Future.get()
Exception Handling Uncaught exceptions go to UncaughtExceptionHandler Exceptions are wrapped in ExecutionException in Future
Callable Support No Yes
Rejection Throws RejectedExecutionException Same
When to Use Fire-and-forget tasks Tasks requiring results or exception handling

Example:

```java
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(5);

// execute - no result
executor.execute(() -> System.out.println("Task executed"));

// submit - with Runnable (no result)
Future<?> future1 = executor.submit(() -> System.out.println("Runnable submitted"));
future1.get(); // Returns null

// submit - with Callable (returns result)
Future<String> future2 = executor.submit(() -> {
    Thread.sleep(1000);
    return "Result from Callable";
});
String result = future2.get(); // Blocks until result available

// Exception handling with submit
Future<Void> future3 = executor.submit(() -> {
    throw new RuntimeException("Error");
});
try {
    future3.get(); // Throws ExecutionException containing the error
} catch (ExecutionException e) {
    // Handle the wrapped exception
}
```

11. How do Functional Interfaces and Lambda Expressions work in Java 8?

Answer:
Functional Interface:

· Interface with exactly one abstract method
· Can have multiple default or static methods
· Annotated with @FunctionalInterface (optional)

Lambda Expression:

· Implementation of functional interface using concise syntax
· Enables functional programming in Java
· Works with method references and streams API

Syntax:

```java
// Traditional anonymous class
Runnable r1 = new Runnable() {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
};

// Lambda expression
Runnable r2 = () -> System.out.println("Hello");

// Lambda with parameters
Comparator<String> comp = (s1, s2) -> s1.length() - s2.length();

// Multiple statements in lambda
Predicate<Integer> predicate = (Integer i) -> {
    i = i * 2;
    return i > 10;
};
```

Common Functional Interfaces:

Interface Method Purpose
Predicate<T> test(T t) Boolean condition
Function<T,R> apply(T t) Transform T to R
Consumer<T> accept(T t) Consume T (no return)
Supplier<T> get() Provide T
UnaryOperator<T> apply(T t) Transform T to T

Example:

```java
// Using functional interfaces with lambda
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie", "David");

// Predicate
Predicate<String> startsWithA = name -> name.startsWith("A");
names.stream().filter(startsWithA).forEach(System.out::println);

// Function
Function<String, Integer> nameLength = name -> name.length();
names.stream().map(nameLength).forEach(System.out::println);

// Method reference - equivalent to lambda
names.forEach(System.out::println); // Not names.forEach(name -> System.out.println(name))
```

