13. How does the Optional class prevent NullPointerException? Name three terminal methods of Optional.

Answer:
Optional is a container object that may or may not contain a non-null value. It provides a functional approach to handle nullable values.

Key Benefits:

· Forces explicit handling of possible null values
· Provides fluent API for functional composition
· Reduces boilerplate null checks
· Helps prevent NullPointerException

Common Terminal Methods:

1. get() - Returns value if present, throws NoSuchElementException if empty
2. orElse(T other) - Returns value if present, otherwise returns the default value
3. orElseGet(Supplier<? extends T> other) - Returns value if present, otherwise invokes Supplier

Example:

```java
// Without Optional - prone to NPE
String name = getUserName();
if (name != null) {
    System.out.println(name.toUpperCase());
}

// With Optional
Optional<String> optName = Optional.ofNullable(getUserName());

// Method 1: Safe access
optName.ifPresent(n -> System.out.println(n.toUpperCase()));

// Method 2: Default value
String name = optName.orElse("Default Name");

// Method 3: Lazy evaluation
String name = optName.orElseGet(() -> fetchFromDatabase());

// Method 4: Throw custom exception
String name = optName.orElseThrow(() -> new RuntimeException("Name not found"));

// Terminal methods example
Optional<String> optional = Optional.of("Hello");

// 1. get() - risky, use with isPresent()
if (optional.isPresent()) {
    String value = optional.get(); // returns "Hello"
}

// 2. orElse() - safe default
String value = optional.orElse("Default"); // "Hello"

// 3. orElseGet() - lazy default
String value = optional.orElseGet(() -> "Default"); // "Hello"

// 4. ifPresent() - execute if value exists
optional.ifPresent(v -> System.out.println("Value: " + v));
```

