15. What is the difference between a Shallow Copy and a Deep Copy in Java? How do you implement both?

Answer:

Shallow Copy:

· Creates new object but shares references to mutable objects
· Only top-level primitive fields are copied
· Changes in copied object's nested objects affect original

Deep Copy:

· Creates completely independent copy
· All nested objects are recursively copied
· No shared references between original and copy

Implementation Methods:

Shallow Copy:

```java
// Using clone() with default implementation
class Employee implements Cloneable {
    String name;
    Address address; // Reference object
    
    @Override
    protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
        return super.clone(); // Shallow copy
    }
}

// Copy constructor (shallow)
Employee shallowCopy = new Employee(original);
```

Deep Copy:

```java
// Using clone() with custom implementation
class Employee implements Cloneable {
    String name;
    Address address;
    
    @Override
    protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
        Employee cloned = (Employee) super.clone();
        cloned.address = (Address) address.clone(); // Deep clone
        return cloned;
    }
}

// Using serialization
public static <T> T deepCopy(T object) {
    try {
        ByteArrayOutputStream baos = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
        ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(baos);
        oos.writeObject(object);
        ByteArrayInputStream bais = new ByteArrayInputStream(baos.toByteArray());
        ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(bais);
        return (T) ois.readObject();
    } catch (Exception e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
        return null;
    }
}

// Using copy libraries (Gson)
Gson gson = new Gson();
Employee deepCopy = gson.fromJson(gson.toJson(original), Employee.class);
```

