16. What is the Inversion of Control (IoC) principle, and how does the Spring Container implement it?

Answer:
Inversion of Control (IoC): Design principle where the control of object creation and lifecycle is inverted from the application to the container.

Traditional Approach:

```java
// Tight coupling - application creates dependencies
class Service {
    private Repository repository;
    public Service() {
        repository = new Repository(); // Hardcoded instantiation
    }
}
```

IoC Approach:

```java
// Loose coupling - container manages dependencies
class Service {
    private Repository repository;
    public Service(Repository repository) { // Constructor injection
        this.repository = repository;
    }
}
```

Spring Container Implementation:

1. BeanFactory: Basic IoC container
2. ApplicationContext: Advanced container with enterprise services

Core Components:

· Configuration: XML, Java annotations, or Java config classes
· Bean Definition: Metadata about beans (scope, lifecycle, dependencies)
· Dependency Injection: Constructor, setter, or field injection
· Bean Lifecycle: Creation, initialization, usage, destruction

Types of IoC:

1. Setter Injection: Via setter methods
2. Constructor Injection: Via constructors (preferred)
3. Field Injection: Direct field assignment (not recommended)

17. Differentiate between Constructor Injection and Setter Injection. Which one is preferred and why?

Answer:

Feature Constructor Injection Setter Injection
Mandatory Dependencies Enforced Not enforced
Immutability Supports (final fields) No
Testing Easier (clear dependencies) More challenging (setters required)
Circular Dependencies Can cause issues Can resolve with @Lazy
Over-injection Harder to have too many parameters Easier to add unnecessary dependencies
Validation Ensures bean is fully initialized Bean may be partially initialized

Constructor Injection (Recommended):

```java
@Component
public class UserService {
    private final UserRepository userRepository;
    private final EmailService emailService;
    
    public UserService(UserRepository userRepository, EmailService emailService) {
        this.userRepository = userRepository; // Mandatory dependencies
        this.emailService = emailService;
    }
}
```

Setter Injection:

```java
@Component
public class UserService {
    private UserRepository userRepository;
    private EmailService emailService;
    
    @Autowired // Optional dependency
    public void setEmailService(EmailService emailService) {
        this.emailService = emailService;
    }
    
    public void setUserRepository(UserRepository userRepository) {
        this.userRepository = userRepository;
    }
}
```

Why Constructor Injection is Preferred:

1. Immutability: Fields can be final
2. Clarity: Clear which dependencies are required
3. Testing: Easy to instantiate with mock dependencies
4. Safety: Avoids null pointer exceptions
5. Best Practice: Spring officially recommends constructor injection

18. Explain the Bean lifecycle phases in a Spring container.

Answer:
Spring Bean lifecycle consists of the following phases:

1. Instantiation: Container creates bean instance using constructor
2. Property Population: Setter methods are called (Dependency Injection)
3. BeanNameAware: setBeanName() called if bean implements BeanNameAware
4. BeanFactoryAware: setBeanFactory() called if implements BeanFactoryAware
5. ApplicationContextAware: setApplicationContext() called if implements ApplicationContextAware
6. Pre-Initialization: BeanPostProcessor.postProcessBeforeInitialization() called
7. Initialization:
   · @PostConstruct method called
   · InitializingBean.afterPropertiesSet() called
   · Custom init-method called
8. Post-Initialization: BeanPostProcessor.postProcessAfterInitialization() called
9. Ready to Use: Bean fully initialized and ready for use
10. Destruction:
    · @PreDestroy method called
    · DisposableBean.destroy() called
    · Custom destroy-method called

Example:

```java
@Component
public class LifecycleBean implements BeanNameAware, BeanFactoryAware, ApplicationContextAware, 
                                      InitializingBean, DisposableBean {
    
    @PostConstruct
    public void init() {
        System.out.println("PostConstruct called");
    }
    
    @PreDestroy
    public void destroyMethod() {
        System.out.println("PreDestroy called");
    }
    
    @Override
    public void afterPropertiesSet() throws Exception {
        System.out.println("InitializingBean called");
    }
    
    @Override
    public void destroy() throws Exception {
        System.out.println("DisposableBean called");
    }
    
    @Override
    public void setBeanFactory(BeanFactory beanFactory) throws BeansException {
        System.out.println("BeanFactoryAware called");
    }
    
    @Override
    public void setBeanName(String name) {
        System.out.println("BeanNameAware called");
    }
    
    @Override
    public void setApplicationContext(ApplicationContext context) throws BeansException {
        System.out.println("ApplicationContextAware called");
    }
}
```

19. What are the different Spring Bean scopes? How does a Singleton bean interact safely with a Prototype bean?

Answer:

Scope Description Usage
Singleton One instance per container (default) Stateless beans
Prototype New instance each time requested Stateful beans
Request One instance per HTTP request Web applications
Session One instance per HTTP session Web applications
Application One instance per ServletContext Web applications
WebSocket One instance per WebSocket WebSocket applications

Singleton + Prototype Interaction Problem:
When a singleton bean has a prototype bean as dependency, the prototype bean is only created once during singleton initialization.

Solution 1: Method Injection with @Lookup

```java
@Component
public class SingletonBean {
    
    @Lookup
    public PrototypeBean getPrototypeBean() {
        return null; // Spring will override this method
    }
    
    public void doSomething() {
        PrototypeBean bean = getPrototypeBean(); // New instance each call
        bean.process();
    }
}
```

Solution 2: ApplicationContextAware

```java
@Component
public class SingletonBean implements ApplicationContextAware {
    
    private ApplicationContext applicationContext;
    
    @Override
    public void setApplicationContext(ApplicationContext context) {
        this.applicationContext = context;
    }
    
    public void doSomething() {
        PrototypeBean bean = applicationContext.getBean(PrototypeBean.class);
        bean.process();
    }
}
```

Solution 3: ObjectFactory/Provider

```java
@Component
public class SingletonBean {
    
    @Autowired
    private ObjectFactory<PrototypeBean> prototypeFactory;
    
    public void doSomething() {
        PrototypeBean bean = prototypeFactory.getObject();
        bean.process();
    }
}
```

20. What is the purpose of the @Autowired annotation? How does it resolve ambiguity if multiple beans of the same type exist?

Answer:
@Autowired enables dependency injection by automatically wiring beans based on type.

Resolution Strategies:

1. @Primary: Marks one bean as primary candidate
2. @Qualifier: Specifies bean name to inject
3. Field/Parameter Name: Spring uses name as fallback

Example:

```java
// Multiple beans of same type
@Configuration
public class AppConfig {
    @Bean
    public DatabaseService mysqlService() {
        return new MySQLService();
    }
    
    @Bean
    @Primary
    public DatabaseService postgresService() {
        return new PostgresService(); // Primary bean
    }
    
    @Bean
    @Qualifier("oracle")
    public DatabaseService oracleService() {
        return new OracleService();
    }
}

// Resolving ambiguity
@Service
public class UserService {
    
    // 1. Using @Primary (will use postgresService)
    @Autowired
    private DatabaseService primaryService;
    
    // 2. Using @Qualifier
    @Autowired
    @Qualifier("oracle")
    private DatabaseService oracleService;
    
    // 3. Using field name (injects mysqlService)
    @Autowired
    private DatabaseService mysqlService;
    
    // 4. Using constructor with @Qualifier
    private DatabaseService selectedService;
    
    public UserService(@Qualifier("mysqlService") DatabaseService service) {
        this.selectedService = service;
    }
}
```

@Autowired Rules:

· Can be applied to constructors, methods, parameters, fields
· required = false makes dependency optional
· Single constructor doesn't require @Autowired
· Works with ApplicationContext.getBean()

21. Explain the difference between @Component, @Service, @Repository, and @Controller.

Answer:
