22. How does Spring's Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP) work? Define Advice, Pointcut, and JoinPoint.

Answer:
AOP enables separation of cross-cutting concerns (logging, security, transactions) from business logic.

Core Concepts:

Term Definition Example
Aspect Module containing cross-cutting concerns @Aspect class
Advice Action to be taken at joinpoint @Before, @After, @Around
Pointcut Expression matching joinpoints @Pointcut("execution(* com.example.*.*(..))")
JoinPoint Point during execution (method call, exception) Method execution
Weaving Integrating advice with target code Compile-time, load-time, runtime

Example:

```java
@Aspect
@Component
public class LoggingAspect {
    
    // Pointcut definition
    @Pointcut("execution(* com.example.service.*.*(..))")
    public void serviceLayer() {}
    
    // Before advice
    @Before("serviceLayer()")
    public void beforeServiceCall(JoinPoint joinPoint) {
        System.out.println("Before: " + joinPoint.getSignature().getName());
    }
    
    // After returning advice
    @AfterReturning(pointcut = "serviceLayer()", returning = "result")
    public void afterReturning(JoinPoint joinPoint, Object result) {
        System.out.println("Returned: " + result);
    }
    
    // Around advice - most powerful
    @Around("serviceLayer()")
    public Object aroundService(ProceedingJoinPoint joinPoint) throws Throwable {
        long start = System.currentTimeMillis();
        try {
            Object result = joinPoint.proceed(); // Execute method
            long duration = System.currentTimeMillis() - start;
            System.out.println("Time taken: " + duration + "ms");
            return result;
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
            throw e;
        }
    }
}
```

Spring AOP vs AspectJ:

· Spring AOP: Proxy-based, runtime weaving, method interception only
· AspectJ: Compile-time/load-time weaving, all joinpoints

