31. Explain the "N+1 Select Problem" in Hibernate. How do you resolve it?

Answer:
The N+1 problem occurs when fetching entities with associations where:

· 1 query fetches the parent entities
· N queries fetch the child associations for each parent

Example of N+1 Problem:

```java
// Entity
@Entity
public class Post {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "post", fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    private List<Comment> comments;
}

// Query - Causes N+1
List<Post> posts = entityManager
    .createQuery("SELECT p FROM Post p")
    .getResultList();

for (Post post : posts) { // For each post
    post.getComments().size(); // Triggers SELECT query for comments
}
// Result: 1 query for posts + N queries for comments
```

Solutions:

1. JOIN FETCH

```java
@Query("SELECT p FROM Post p JOIN FETCH p.comments")
List<Post> findAllWithComments();

// Or in HQL
List<Post> posts = entityManager
    .createQuery("SELECT p FROM Post p JOIN FETCH p.comments")
    .getResultList();
```

2. EntityGraph

```java
// Named EntityGraph
@Entity
@NamedEntityGraph(name = "Post.comments", attributeNodes = @NamedAttributeNode("comments"))
public class Post {
    // ...
}

// Using EntityGraph
@EntityGraph(value = "Post.comments")
@Query("SELECT p FROM Post p")
List<Post> findAllWithComments();

// Dynamic EntityGraph
EntityGraph<Post> graph = entityManager.createEntityGraph(Post.class);
graph.addAttributeNodes("comments");
Map<String, Object> hints = new HashMap<>();
hints.put("javax.persistence.fetchgraph", graph);
List<Post> posts = entityManager
    .createQuery("SELECT p FROM Post p")
    .setHint("javax.persistence.fetchgraph", graph)
    .getResultList();
```

3. Batch Fetching

```properties
# application.properties
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.default_batch_fetch_size=10
```

```java
@Entity
public class Post {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "post", fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    @BatchSize(size = 10)
    private List<Comment> comments;
}
```

4. Subselect

```java
@Entity
public class Post {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "post", fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    @Fetch(FetchMode.SUBSELECT)
    private List<Comment> comments;
}
```

32. What is the difference between FetchType.LAZY and FetchType.EAGER?

Answer:

Feature LAZY EAGER
When Loaded Loaded on access Loaded immediately with parent
Performance Better initial fetch Poor initial fetch (cartesian product)
Memory Usage Less memory initially More memory upfront
N+1 Problem Can cause N+1 Might cause larger N+1
Default For @OneToMany, @ManyToMany @ManyToOne, @OneToOne
Usage Preferred generally Only if always needed

Example:

```java
@Entity
public class Post {
    @Id
    private Long id;
    private String title;
    
    // LAZY - Loaded when accessed
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "post", fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    private List<Comment> comments;
    
    // EAGER - Loaded immediately
    @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.EAGER)
    private Author author;
}

// LAZY behavior
Post post = session.get(Post.class, 1L);
// Only Post fetched, comments not loaded yet
List<Comment> comments = post.getComments(); // Now comments are loaded

// EAGER behavior
Post post = session.get(Post.class, 1L);
// Post and Author both fetched in single query (JOIN)
```

When to Use Each:

· LAZY: Most of the time, especially for large collections
· EAGER: Only when you always need the association
· Best Practice: Default to LAZY, use JOIN FETCH when needed

33. How do you implement Pagination and Sorting using Spring Data JPA?

Answer:
