1. Using Pageable Interface:

```java
// Repository method
public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
    Page<User> findByDepartment(String department, Pageable pageable);
    Slice<User> findUsersByAgeGreaterThan(int age, Pageable pageable);
}

// Usage
Pageable pageable = PageRequest.of(
    page,                      // Page number (0-indexed)
    size,                      // Page size
    Sort.by(Sort.Direction.DESC, "name") // Sorting
);

Page<User> userPage = userRepository.findByDepartment("IT", pageable);
List<User> users = userPage.getContent();
int totalPages = userPage.getTotalPages();
long totalElements = userPage.getTotalElements();
boolean isFirst = userPage.isFirst();
boolean isLast = userPage.isLast();
```

2. Using Sort Object:

```java
// Sorting only (no pagination)
Sort sort = Sort.by("name").descending()
    .and(Sort.by("age").ascending());
List<User> users = userRepository.findAll(sort);

// Custom Sort with pagination
Pageable pageable = PageRequest.of(0, 10, Sort.by(
    Sort.Order.desc("createdDate"),
    Sort.Order.asc("id")
));
```

3. Using Native Queries:

```java
@Query(value = "SELECT * FROM users u WHERE u.department = ?1",
       countQuery = "SELECT count(*) FROM users u WHERE u.department = ?1",
       nativeQuery = true)
Page<User> findByDepartmentNative(String department, Pageable pageable);
```

4. Slicing (for large datasets without total count):

```java
public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
    Slice<User> findByDepartment(String department, Pageable pageable);
}

// Slice doesn't query total count, better performance for large datasets
Slice<User> userSlice = userRepository.findByDepartment("IT", pageable);
boolean hasNext = userSlice.hasNext();
boolean hasPrevious = userSlice.hasPrevious();
```

5. Custom Pagination Query:

```java
public class CustomUserRepository {
    @PersistenceContext
    private EntityManager entityManager;
    
    public Page<User> findUsersCustom(String search, Pageable pageable) {
        // Build query
        String query = "SELECT u FROM User u WHERE LOWER(u.name) LIKE LOWER(:search)";
        TypedQuery<User> typedQuery = entityManager.createQuery(query, User.class);
        typedQuery.setParameter("search", "%" + search + "%");
        
        // Count query
        String countQuery = "SELECT COUNT(u) FROM User u WHERE LOWER(u.name) LIKE LOWER(:search)";
        TypedQuery<Long> countTypedQuery = entityManager.createQuery(countQuery, Long.class);
        countTypedQuery.setParameter("search", "%" + search + "%");
        
        // Apply pagination
        typedQuery.setFirstResult((int) pageable.getOffset());
        typedQuery.setMaxResults(pageable.getPageSize());
        
        return new PageImpl<>(typedQuery.getResultList(), 
                              pageable, 
                              countTypedQuery.getSingleResult());
    }
}
```

34. What is the difference between Session.get() and Session.load() (or findById() vs getReferenceById())?

Answer:

Feature get() / findById() load() / getReferenceById()
Loading Immediately loads entity Returns proxy, loads lazily
Database Hit Always hits database May not hit database until needed
Performance Slower (always DB access) Faster (proxy creation)
Null Return Returns null if not found Throws EntityNotFoundException if accessed
Caching Checks cache first then DB Checks cache, then creates proxy
Use Case When you need data immediately When you need reference for association

Example:

```java
// Session.get() vs Session.load()
User user1 = session.get(User.class, 1L);
// Immediately executes: SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = 1

User user2 = session.load(User.class, 2L);
// No SQL executed, returns proxy object
String name = user2.getName();
// Now SQL is executed to load the data

// Spring Data JPA equivalents
public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
    // findById() - equivalent to Session.get()
    Optional<User> findById(Long id);
    
    // getReferenceById() - equivalent to Session.load()
    User getReferenceById(Long id);
}

// Usage
// findById()
User user1 = userRepository.findById(1L).orElse(null);
// Executes SELECT immediately

// getReferenceById()
User user2 = userRepository.getReferenceById(1L);
// No SELECT executed, returns proxy
String name = user2.getName();
// SELECT executed on access
```

When to Use:

· Use findById() when you need to check existence
· Use getReferenceById() when:
  · Setting associations to avoid unnecessary SELECTs
  · Creating new entities with references
  · You're sure the entity exists

35. Explain First-level cache vs Second-level cache in Hibernate.

Answer:

Feature First-Level Cache Second-Level Cache
Scope Session/EntityManager SessionFactory/EntityManagerFactory
Visibility Within same session only Across all sessions
Enabled By Default Yes No
Cache Type Transactional/Application SessionFactory/Cluster
Eviction Automatic at session end Configurable
Performance Fast but limited Slower but broader
Store Memory only Memory/disk/external

First-Level Cache:

```java
Session session = sessionFactory.openSession();
Transaction tx = session.beginTransaction();

User user1 = session.get(User.class, 1L);
// SELECT executed once

User user2 = session.get(User.class, 1L);
// Returns from cache, no SELECT executed

session.evict(user1); // Remove from cache
User user3 = session.get(User.class, 1L);
// SELECT executed again

tx.commit();
session.close(); // Cache cleared
```

Second-Level Cache Configuration:

```properties
# Enable second-level cache
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.cache.use_second_level_cache=true

# Cache provider (EHCache, Hazelcast, Infinispan)
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.cache.region.factory_class=org.hibernate.cache.ehcache.EhCacheRegionFactory

# Enable query cache
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.cache.use_query_cache=true
```

Entity Annotation:

```java
@Entity
@Cacheable
@org.hibernate.annotations.Cache(usage = CacheConcurrencyStrategy.READ_WRITE)
public class User {
    @Id
    private Long id;
    private String name;
    private String email;
}
```

Cache Strategies:

Strategy Description Use Case
READ_ONLY Immutable data Reference data
NONSTRICT_READ_WRITE Rarely updated Lookup tables
READ_WRITE Frequently updated Transactional data
TRANSACTIONAL JTA transactions Distributed transactions

