36. How do you handle transaction management in Spring Boot using the @Transactional annotation? What is propagation?

Answer:
@Transactional provides declarative transaction management.

Key Attributes:

```java
@Transactional(
    propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED,    // Default
    isolation = Isolation.DEFAULT,
    timeout = 30,
    readOnly = false,
    rollbackFor = Exception.class,
    noRollbackFor = RuntimeException.class
)
```

Propagation Types:

Propagation Description
REQUIRED Join existing tx or create new
REQUIRES_NEW Suspend existing, create new
MANDATORY Require existing tx, throw if none
NESTED Execute nested transaction
SUPPORTS Join if exists, else non-tx
NOT_SUPPORTED Execute non-transactionally
NEVER Throw if transaction exists

Example:

```java
@Service
public class UserService {
    
    // Default propagation (REQUIRED)
    @Transactional
    public void createUser(User user) {
        userRepository.save(user);
        // Throws exception, everything rolls back
    }
    
    // REQUIRES_NEW - always new transaction
    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void sendNotification(User user) {
        // Always in new transaction
        notificationService.send(user);
    }
    
    // NESTED - savepoint for partial rollback
    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.NESTED)
    public void processUser(User user) {
        userRepository.save(user);
        try {
            userRepository.process(); // Nested transaction
        } catch (Exception e) {
            // Outer transaction can continue
        }
    }
    
    // Read-only optimization
    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public User findUser(Long id) {
        return userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);
    }
    
    // Transactional with timeout
    @Transactional(timeout = 10)
    public void longProcess() {
        // Must complete within 10 seconds
    }
    
    // Rollback for specific exceptions
    @Transactional(rollbackFor = SQLException.class)
    public void saveData() throws SQLException {
        // Rolls back on SQLException but not RuntimeException
    }
}
```

Best Practices:

1. Apply to service layer methods, not repository
2. Keep transactions short-lived
3. Use readOnly for query methods
4. Avoid calling @Transactional methods within same class
5. Be careful with lazy loading outside transaction

37. What is the difference between Optimistic Locking and Pessimistic Locking in JPA?

Answer:

Optimistic Locking:

· Assumes conflicts are rare
· Uses version number or timestamp
· Checks version on update
· Throws OptimisticLockException on conflict

Pessimistic Locking:

· Assumes conflicts are frequent
· Locks record during transaction
· Other transactions block
· Higher overhead
· Used for critical data

Optimistic Locking Example:

```java
@Entity
public class Product {
    @Id
    private Long id;
    
    @Version
    private Long version; // Incremented on each update
    
    private String name;
    private int quantity;
}

// Usage - handles conflict
@Transactional
public void updateProduct(Long id, int quantity) {
    Product product = productRepository.findById(id).orElseThrow();
    product.setQuantity(quantity);
    // When saving, version check prevents stale updates
    productRepository.save(product);
}

// Handling OptimisticLockException
try {
    updateProduct(1L, 100);
} catch (OptimisticLockException e) {
    // Retry or notify user
}
```

Pessimistic Locking Example:

```java
@Repository
public interface ProductRepository extends JpaRepository<Product, Long> {
    
    @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
    @Query("SELECT p FROM Product p WHERE p.id = :id")
    Optional<Product> findByIdWithPessimisticLock(@Param("id") Long id);
}

// Usage
@Transactional
public void updateProductWithLock(Long id, int quantity) {
    Product product = productRepository.findByIdWithPessimisticLock(id).orElseThrow();
    product.setQuantity(quantity);
    productRepository.save(product);
    // Lock released when transaction commits
}
```

Lock Types:

Lock Mode Description
PESSIMISTIC_READ Shared lock, others can read but not write
PESSIMISTIC_WRITE Exclusive lock, others can't read or write
PESSIMISTIC_FORCE_INCREMENT Pessimistic write with version increment

